column169: Description Of Events

AT THE UPS MIAMI FLORIDA FACILITY, ONE BLACK SHRINKED WRAPPED WOODEN SKID SHIPPING AIR CARGO SERVICE TO COLOMBIA WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN FLAMMABLE PRODUCTS. DURING THE SCREENING PROCESS WHILE CUTTING THE BLACK SHRINK WRAPPING, SEVERAL BOXES WERE FOUND WITH CLASS NINE DIAMOND LABELS AND AIR LIMITED QUANTITY MARKS. OTHER BOXES WERE FOUND WITH GROUND LIMITED QUANTITY MARKS. INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS OF THESE BOXES FOUND NUMEROUS FLAMMABLE PERFUMERY PRODUCTS. THE FREIGHT WAS OFFERED FOR AIR TRANSPORTATION TO UPS AIR CARGO WITHOUT ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BLACK SHRINK WRAPPING. THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE AIR WAYBILL THAT DANGEROUS GOOD PRODUCTS WERE BEING SHIPPED AIR SERVICE.  THE ISSUING CARRIER'S AGENT NAME AND CITY ON THE AIR WAYBILL IS ALSEATRANS US, 1665 NW 102ND AV, SUITE 108, MIAMI FL, 33172, US. THE SHIPPER'S NAME AND ADDRESS ON THE AIR WAYBILL IS MSL INTL GROUP, LLC, 1665 NW 102ND AV, MIAMI FL US.

When this package was found it was wet and leaking. with further inspection it was discovered that the bottles of muriatic acid had been leaking inside the box causing the exterior of the box to corrode. Along with all 4 bottles having loose caps. resulting in the internal leakage and corrosion of the box.

column43: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column169: At PDX, on 8/19/2024, Delta's Dangerous Goods Management team received an incident report where a shipment that contained dry ice was transported from LAX to PDX undeclared. The courier whom picked up the packages stated there was 20 kg of dry ice per container. However, there was no dry ice statement on the air waybill, no Special Handling Code(SPL) entries or NOTOC produced for the flight. Additionally, there were no labels or markings indicating dry ice on the packages. The description noted in the cargo booking system states,"empty Packaging, comat non haz". This event is under investigation.
column170: Immediate Corrective actions. The root cause analysis is on-going: - Alerted shipper and initiated investigation on the source of their"booking" failure - Shippefs booking agent addressed internally - FAA investigation initiated Comprehensive corrective actions will be determined/developed upon completion of the investigation.

On August 16, 2024, ten (10) 1-gallon pails of contact cement were crushed in transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the contact cement-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, and ten (10) 1-gallon pails of contact cement were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

column169: While in transit the driver noticed material on the side of his tank and pulled off and inspected the trailer 1030et. He discovered the the seal on the manhole was not seating properly and the material was seeping out onto the tank. They sent out a new tank and a temporary containment so that the material could be safely transferred. The new tank showed up at 1330et and the temporary containment arrived at 1600et. They then set up the containment and transferred the material into the new tank. The material that got on the side of the tank was cleaned off and put into a salvage drum for proper disposal. The transfer and break down of the containment took about an hour and they were back on the road by 1700et.
column170: The Tanker was taken to the shop for repairs it is believed that the gasket was damaged but at this time the trailer is still weighting for repairs.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XEN experienced a roadside release of UN1139 SRW Low Gloss X-Treme  from (5) 5-gallon metal pails. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to an 8’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor. Approximately 10 ounces of product impacted the trailers undercarriage and a 1’ x 1’ area of the concrete lot below. The pails were crushed due to improper securement of the pallet and load shift. The impacted area was cleaned with absorbents and pads which were containerized along with impacted debris into a 55- gallon metal drum. The damaged pails were containerized into a 55-gallon metal and 15-gallon poly drums. The waste was transported to XPO Logistics terminal located in Eagan, MN for terminal personnel to manage.

On 08/21/2024 at approximately 1330, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 317901 at the hub facility in Memphis, reporting spillage from undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 3 - 1 gallon plastic containers packaging inside of a fiberboard box.  Each plastic container contained muriatic acid.  The shipment was discovered to a have spilled from the closure of each of the plastic containers.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, as it did not display the required markings, labeling, packaging and paparwork.  The shipment has been place in a salvage drum and is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.  Upon release by the FAA, the shipment will be sent for disposal.

On August 13, 2024, at 2050 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Roadrunner personnel in Conley, Georgia regarding the release of Socar Brake Wash (UN1208, Hexanes, 3, II). Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 20 gallons of Socar Brake Wash (UN1208, Hexanes, 3, II) from (1) 55-gallon DM. The release was caused by a forklift puncture and impacted a 15ft x 20ft area of concrete on the dock floor. Contractors reported that the release had completely evaporated by the time they arrived. Contractors placed the damaged drum with the remaining product into a 65-gallon metal overpack then staged the waste onsite for proper disposal.

column169: On 8/27/2024, the BNSF Los Angeles hub personnel reported Unit ESTU 500350 (Waybill Hazardous) as leaking a substance from the middle of the container that did reach the ground after unit de   ramped from a train. Unit was taken to the Hazmat Pit for safety. On the behalf of the shipper, approved contractor United Pumping was contacted and dispatched to complete inspection. Interior inspection revealed palatized cases, palletized gallon drums and 2 IBC Totes of Sulfuric Acid in 2 rows, stacked 2 high in the nose throughout the container. Source of the leak was determined to be 2 IBC Totes in the middle of the unit. The cause for the Leak was determined to be 2 IBC Totes appeared to have a pre   existing creases near the top that caused the totes plastic to break, creating package failure contributing to the material leak. Total quantity of leaked liquid was approximately 10 gallons of product, 5 gallons from each IBC Tote.

On 8/22/2024, at 1353 hours, CSXT personnel at the Walbridge Yard discovered FHRX135943, a loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten, with a vapor release from the connection between the manway nozzle and the manway cover. The car was isolated and the shipper, Marathon Petroleum Company, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024082200196). CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager Scott Karcher found the manway gasket to be improperly installed (misaligned) which allowed for a vapor release. The damaged gasket was removed, a new gasket was installed, and the manway was secured for transportation.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Jennifer Johnson 209-986-1196). This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.

column169: On 8/19/2024 at approximately 2100, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 3667328 at the station in Portland, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of a polystyrene package, containing various food items packed on wet ice, along with two plastic containers of "Multi-Clor".  The outer packaging appeared to colapse under the weight, exposing the shipment's contents.  An online safety data sheet, retrieved by Dangerous Goods Administration, classified "Multi-Clor" as UN 1791 Hypochlorite solution.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA  Regulations, as it was not completed with the required markings, labeling, packaging or paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

On August 29, 2024 at 0454 ET, an XPO Logistics tractor trailer was exiting I-85 SB onto W.T. Harris Blvd in Charlotte, NC, when the unit rolled over. As a result of the accident (4) 275-gallon poly totes were structurally damaged but still in tact. On September 18, 2024, XPO Logistics in Mississauga, ON notified ERTS of the four totes sitting on their dock needing a transfer. The tote were originally to ship onto the consignee, however the shipper and consignee confirmed the totes needed to be disposed of. ERTS dispatched contractors with specialty totes to complete the transfer of all 4 totes into new ones on September 21, 2024. The crew confirmed there was approximately 1-teaspoon of dried product on the tote body as a result of the roll over accident. All product was successfully transferred from the damaged totes into new ones with no further incident or release. The waste was staged onsite at XPO in Mississauga for terminal personnel to manage.

Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of a total of 2 gallons of Transchem Muriatic Acid (UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid Solution, 8, II) from a box containing (4) 1-gallon plastic pails. The release was due to a load shift and impacted a 6ft x 6ft area on the trailer floor and the outer boxes of other cargo. Contractors neutralized and cleaned the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. Thirty-four 1-gallon plastic pails of recovered product were collected and containerized in (2) 55-gallon DF’s. All waste was containerized in (1) 55-gallon DM, and (1) 55-gallon DF, then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column169: On 08-12-2024 a CN transportation employee smelled a strong chemical odor emanating from tank car #TAEX 1856 while working. in the Kirk Yard in Gary, IN. The CN Dangerous Goods Team was notified and responded to the area to investigate.  An assessment of tank car # TAEX 1856 (Residue/UN 1136/Class 3) revealed a vapor release from the pressure relief device which was detected audibly and by the use of a combustible gas detector along with a leak detecting solution. A pressure test was performed via the vapor valve which revealed the tank car to have an internal pressure of 5 psi. The low pressure indicated the pressure relief device was faulty and not performing as intended, allowing vapors to escape.  The tank car was moved to an isolation track where the remaining internal pressure was vented through a scrubbing media which stopped the leak. The pressure relief device was then removed and replaced with a blind flange to prevent further leakage. The shipper of record was notified via Chemtrec that the car would require repair and re-qualification by a certified tank car repair facility prior to being released for continued transportation.

Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 45'X1' area of the trailer floor and a 10'x2' area of the asphalt underneath the trailer. An estimated ten (10) gallons of material was released due to a pallet nail puncture. Contractors overpacked the two drums, neutralized the area, deployed absorbents, and cleaned up the released material. The damaged drum, impacted drum, and recovered material were placed into three (3) 55-gallon poly drums and was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization.

column169: During a drum transfer operation between trailers at Veolia's Schenectady, NY 10 day intransit facility, a Veolia employee accidentally punctured a 55-gallon steel drum containing Class 9 hazardous waste liquid. The puncture was caused by an unnoticed metal burr on the drum cart. The release duration was less than one minute resulting in approximately 1 liter of liquid leaked onto the trailer floor. The spill was cleaned using spill pads and absorbent material and the damaged drum was overpacked into an 85-gallon salvage drum for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column170: The Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill on 8/7/24 and performed an investigation into the incident. The investigation found the employee was unaware of the defect with the drum cart. Following the incident, the employee inspected the drum cart and identified the burr that pierced the drum. The drum cart was placed out of service.   Corrective Actions: 1. Inspect and maintain drum handling equipment regularly. 2. Reinforce proper drum handling procedures with employees. 3. Implement additional safety checks before drum transfers.

column169: On August 8, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1760 was crushed in transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnivroServe (ES) to remediate the impacted site. Upon arrival, ES was notified that personnel for R+L carriers had deployed granular absorbents to the trailer interior and had station the damaged pail on the dock floor. ES personnel began by placing the damaged product pail into one (1) 55-gallon drum. They then utilized absorbent rags to clean and neutralize the dock floor. All spent absorbents were then placed into the same 55-gallon drum as the product pail.

column169: On August 29, 2024, one (1) 15-gallon drum of UN3267 was damaged by other freight and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. The crew overpacked the damaged drum into one (1) 95-gallon drum. FCE utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted site. After all freight was neutralized, all impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: On August 16, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of hydrochloric acid was punctured by a skid and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from TPM Group (TPM) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the hydrochloric acid-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

On August 5, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3082 was damaged in a load shift and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior and terminal lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works (EW) to remediate the impacted site. EW personnel collected one (1) damaged 55-gallon drum of UN 3082 and containerized it in one (1) 95-gallon overpack. Crews then deployed granular absorbents and worked them in using hand tools. Once collected, EW personnel utilized absorbent wipes to remediate any residual product. All UN 3082 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 95-gallon overpack and one (1) 55-gallon drum.

column169: A return, Generator with gas still in tank, was sent through the system in an unmarked U-Haul box. Package was placed on van line and went overhead. Damage occurred by simulator at Load-side 135. The package showed no external indications of gasoline, including smell, prior to spill.  An employee handling the package after the spill, accidently rubbed their eye. The eye wash station was used before leaving for the emergency room. Chemical spill occurred inside trailer as well, number of packages affected unknown. Neutralizer used on the spill.
No comments provided.

column43: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column169: The bottle of nitric acid was packed in accordance with lab pack standards and shipped to the 10-day transfer facility in Indianapolis. The package was transferred onto an on-site trailer at the facility and placed on top of a 5-gallon pail unsecured. When the trailer was subsequently moved into the dock, the lab pack box fell 18 inches and approximately 1/2 quart of nitric acid leaked from the package. The original container and the clean up residue were overpacked in a 15-gallon poly drum with vermiculite. The containers were not fully blocked and braced since the trailer was not leaving the site.
column170: Ensure all containers are secured prior to movement of trailer.

column169: During a trailer loading operation at Veolia's 10-day in-transit facility in Port Allen, Louisiana, an employee observed a small puddle of liquid on the ground beneath a recently moved pallet. Upon closer examination, it was discovered that one of the drums on the pallet had sustained a minor gash near its base. The leak was estimated to be approximately half an ounce of liquid. The spill was immediately addressed using oil-dry absorbent material, and the damaged drum was safely transferred into an overpack container to prevent further leakage.
column170: The exact cause and timing of the damage to the drum remain uncertain. However, this incident serves as a reminder of the importance of implementing rigorous inspection protocols for all containers. It also emphasizes the need for exercising extreme caution when handling and moving any type of container. Regular and thorough inspections, combined with careful handling practices, can significantly reduce the risk of similar incidents in the future and ensure safer operations overall.

The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: Possible thermal runaway of a lithium ion battery occurred on flight AA 6271 ALB-ORD on 8/1/2024. CRJ 700 aircraft, N750SK  During the flight the AFT Flight Attendant sat in her jumpseat. At some point during this action, her Electronic Flight Attendant Device (iPhone 12) slid from her pocket and into the gap behind the folding jumpseat. She stood up and realized the phone may have been crunched/damaged in the jumpseat. She noticed a crack in the device's screen.  A few moments later she noticed the phone began to feel warm. She notified the FWD flight attendant of the issue. Together, they took the device to a galley ice tray and drowned the device in ice water and notified the flight deck. At that point, they realized they should be using the aircraft's fire containment bag. They moved the device to the fire containment bag and added more liquid to completely drown the device. Upon arrival into ORD, the fire containment bag containing the damaged device was handed off to a customer service agent. There were no further issues with the damaged device. PLEASE NOTE that the device DID NOT emit smoke, sparks, flames, or any gasses. This should be considered a possible dangerous evolution of heat.

On 8/23/2024 at approximately 1400, Dangerous Goods Adminstration received a call from Employee 5007286 at the hub facility in Memphis, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 1 fiberboard box that contained 3 plastic containers labeled as "Muriatic Acid".  Dangerous Goods Administration obtained an online safety data sheet, which classified the commodity as UN 1789 Hydrochloric Acid.  Two of the three containers leaked from the closure, resulting in spillage.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the requred markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  The spillage also compromised the integrity of the shipping label and the outer package; however, the inner contents are being held, pending an FAA investigation.  The shipment contained the identical contents as were reported in Spill Incident #20260.   This shipper has been placed on embargo list.

The issue was identified, and corrective actions, were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Clay Hester, 912-944-7107).  Emergency response efforts secured the car from leaking; it was held at location pending additional work by a certified tank car repair facility that could performed a qualified repaired.

USING DECISION TREE, RESPONDER WAS LED TO THE CORROSIVE SOLIDS OR LIQUIDS HAZARD CLASS RESPONSE SHEET. TORE OFF 5 INCHES OF PH TAPE AND COULD NOT DEICPHER IF THE TAPE WAS BLUE BECAUSE THAT WAS ALSO THE COLOR OF THE SPILLED LIQUID. RESPONDER STILL USED SODIUM BICARBINATE UNTIL IT RESULTED IN NEUTRAL PH TAPE. THEN CLEANED THE SPILL AND TRANSFERED IT TO THE DMP WHERE RESPONDER COMPLETED THE REST OF THE CLEANUP DMP PROCESS.

XPO Logistics terminal LJB experienced a customer location and roadside release of UN1819 Xcelerator A38 from a 300-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 110-gallons of product released to a 53' x 8' area of the trailer floor, 54' x 8' area of the asphalt roadway, a 54' x 2.5' area of the soil shoulder, and a 30' x 40' area of the customer’s asphalt lot as well as into a storm drain catch basin. Contractors secured the release with absorbents, pads, and boom upon arrival. The crew confirmed the tote was punctured due to improper loading. The material still in the damaged tote was transferred into a new one. Once all free liquid was absorbed, sodium bicarbonate and water were used to rinse the impacted areas to clean and neutralize them. The following day, the crew returned to site with a vac truck and a pressure washer. The impacted catch basin was vacuumed and flushed out. The customer confirmed the pumps were shut off so the material could not migrate from the drains catch basin. The impacted concrete lot at the customers location and the impacted asphalt roadway were then pressure washed, and all material was collected into a vac-truck. Approximately 1300-gallons of impacted wastewater were removed from site pending disposal. (5) 55-gallon poly drums of impacted absorbents, the cut up damaged poly tote, and impacted debris were transported to the XPO Terminal located in Jonesboro, AR for terminal personnel to manage. The impacted soil shoulder was then secured and marked for future remediation.

On Monday, August 5, 2024, a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve appeared to be leaking from tank car # FURX 160111 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Waterloo Yard Master who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car was set out to an isolation track (WA60) for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor.  A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The contractor performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap. It was determined that there was a failure in the sealing surface of the valve seat to include a defective gasket. (The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight and the BOV in the closed position and pinned upon initial inspection). CN emergency response contractor did observe cable seal to be correctly in place. The BOV cap was removed, and it was observed to be leaking past the closed ball.  The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. It was noted that the BOV cap gasket was deformed and was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench. Upon tightening the BOV cap, CN emergency response contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV / Cap.

It was suspected the drum was punctured by a pallet nail. Kolor-Safe neutralizer and absorbents were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. The impacted absorbents were then collected into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum of product was placed into a second 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Schneider Bulk Carriers notified ERTS of a cargo release in Waterloo, IA. It was reported that 2000 gallons of Performance XXL Alkali needs a transload or an off load from trailer # 28902 due to internal valve leaking. The release impacted asphalt and concrete. Update from the driver advised a small 80-gallon pool with product is filled and a second pool was being used to collect product, but the leak was steady.  Clean Harbors arrived on site and advised an estimated 70-gallons were released and caught in the retention pits due to a internal valve leaking. The released product was collected and placed into a 275-gal tote. A vac truck was used to transfer the remainder of product from the tank.  The transfer has been completed. The impacted plastics used for retention were cut and drummed. Due to the potential haz waste properties, (1) 275IBC w/ 70-gallons of Performance XXL Alkali; and (1) 55 DF w/ impacted plastic will be left onsite until the profiling was approved for a receiving facility.

column169: During the transfer of a 551A1 container filled with liquid, oil-based white paint (overpacked into an 851H2) from the customer's storage facility to a Veolia box truck, an incident occurred. As the drum, weighing over 600 pounds, was being positioned onto a pallet inside the Veolia box truck, a leak was detected. To prevent the drum from slipping and potentially injuring personnel, it was promptly secured on the pallet. However, approximately one gallon of the waste material escaped from the drum, contaminating both the pallet and the box truck's floor.  The cause of the leak remains unclear, as the drum's position did not seem to be a contributing factor. Upon inspection, it was discovered that the inner container was missing its bung, which may have played a role in the unexpected release of the waste material.
column170: Following the incident, management reinforced safety protocols by instructing all employees to thoroughly inspect and confirm the secure closure of all containers before initiating any transport or relocation procedures.

On August 5, 2024, at 1631 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Des Moines, Iowa regarding the release of Lactic Acid (UN3265, 8, III). Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of Lactic Acid (UN3265, Corrosive Liquid, acidic, organic, n.o.s., 8, III) from (9) 275-gallon IBC plastic totes. The release was caused by a rollover accident and impacted the trailer floor, and an area of soil. Contractors placed neutralizer and absorbents on the soil in preparation for remedial and restorative activities, and the totes and trailer were transported to a nearby tow facility. At the tow facility there was an additional release of material that impacted a trail of concrete and the inside of a roll-off. Contractors neutralized, and cleaned all impacted areas with absorbents, then transferred the remaining product from the damaged totes into new totes. All waste was collected and containerized in (11) 55-gallon DF’s and (9) 275-gallon IBC plastic totes, then staged onsite for proper disposal.

Internal bottle had a loose cap, it also presents visually as having been crushed or compressed on opposite sides of the bottle, though there's no sign of the outer carton having been impacted adversely. Body of bottle which lost content is intact, there is no sign of leakage there.

All ZeroTol 2.0 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon poly drum that was staged on-site

Contractors overpacked 95-gallon drum, and recovered material was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 23:00 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal NNA. It was reported that approximately 137.5 gallons of UN3266 Natural HDPE FCL13 released from a plastic tote due to a pole on another piece of freight puncturing the tote during the unloading process. The release impacted inside of trailer #3153521 and asphalt. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 180-gallons of product released to a 300-yard x 400-yard are of the asphalt lot as well as the trailer floor. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The remaining material in the tote was transferred into a new one. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized. All impacted absorbents and the cut up poly tote were then containerized into (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Driver approached light at intersection of Old Henry Road and Terra Crossing Blvd. Driver had come to the light and almost stopped when the light turned green. The driver continued to tum left in the outside lane. As he was in the turn, the load took over and he overturned. When the fire dept and hazmat team arrived, they began with pads and oil dry. When the trailer was up righted on 729 gallons remained in compartment 3. Emergency response crews began with GRA-KA T arriving first. They enlisted the help of PECCO and Early Environmental. Later that night, PECCO was to take lead of the remediation and clean-up project. The following day, Shield Environmental was called in to geoprobe the site as well as private property.  Lewis Personnel on site - Timothy Jennings and Raymond Boggs LMPD-Officer Koester Anchorage Middletown Fire Department/HazMat Team - Major Oser Battalion Chief Erica O'Brien, Environmental Specialist Sarah Hettel - KY State EPA Matt Vanderpool - Health Dept & Haz Mat Team Tracie Murphy - Spill Center
column170: Education seems to be the key. Drivers need to understand how complacency and slosh factors with liquid loads can overturn quickly if the mechanics are not understood. Additional training in these areas will be focused upon in safety meetings and quick talks.

column169: Operations Supervisor I Nathan ODonnell contacted safety to report that trailer 572156 caught on fire while on the 241/RDG yard. Operations Supervisor I Nathan ODonnell stated that after ABF Road Driver Terry Schreck arrived at 241/RDG the lead trailer 572156 started smoking. ABF Road Driver Terry S chreck advised that after he arrived at 241/RDG he was about to unhook his set when he noticed the lead trailer 572156 was smoking. ABF Road Driver Terry Schreck advised that he then proceeded to disconnect rear trailer 500713 and converter gear 71708 from the lead trailer. ABF Road Driver Terry Sch reck advised that he then proceeded to move trailer 572156 to the middle of the yard before he disconnected the trailer from tractor 13383. ABF Road Driver Terry Schreck advised that after he disconnected trailer 572156 from the tractor the Reading Fire Department arrived on scene. Deputy Chief Glor e of the Reading Fire Department advised that he believes a pallet of Lithium Ion Batteries shifted during transit. Deputy Chief Glore advised that the battery post may have contacted metal causing them to arc igniting a pallet of writing pens that were incased in carboard that was loaded underneath  the pallet of Lithium Ion Batteries. Deputy Chief Glore advised that the Reading Fire Department was able to put the fire out and made sure no drains or waterways were impacted. Operations Supervisor I Nathan ODonnell advised he will send photos of the damage to safety. Safety contacted CURA and sp oke with Cameron Kerr to conduct cleanup procedures.

column169: PACKAGE ORIGINALLY ARRIVED IN TO LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY UPS WORLDPORT OPERATIONS ON 11-MAY-2024 WHERE IT WAS STAGED FOR CLEARANCE FROM CUSTOMS. PACKAGE WAS RETAINED BY CUSTOMS UNTIL UPS WORLDPORT RESPONDED TO THE IMPORT INSPECT AREA DUE TO THE CUSTOMS AGENT DISCOVERY OF THE UNDECLARED PRODUCTS ON 18-AUGUST-24. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, UPS DISCOVERED (20) FLAMELESS RATION HEATERS CLASSIFIED AS 4.3 DANGEROUS WHEN WET. NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THIS PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER 7V077R, GAIN COSMETIC CO LTD, RM 201, 9, YONGGOK-RO 20BEON-GIL, YANGJI-MYEON, YONGIN 17161 SOUTH KOREA.

column169: Package was found on van line appearing fully undamaged but with a strong chemical odor. Manager isolated package from sort immediately upon discovery due to strong odor, despite package not being labeled as a hazmat. QA investigated package and discovered it was an undeclared hazmat item. Outer packaging would be sufficient for hazmat item within, but is not labeled. Item was placed inside plastic bag within box, but has no additional packing material. Appears likely item moved freely within box, causing dents and forcing liquid to spill via lid seams. Leak fully contained within package.
DESIGNATED RESPONDER FOUND SAID PACKAGE ON THE FLOOR AND IT APPEARD TO BE LEAKING. RESPONDER PLACED SAID PACKAGE INTO SPILL TRAY. CLEANED AREA OF CONTAMINATED DEBRIS. RETURNED TO DMP FOR PROCESSING

column169: car was reported releasing vapor with an audible hiss and odor.  Code 3 arrived and determined that the PRD was releasing.  The pressure was 160 psi and 17" of outage.  Since the car was in outbound, and VOC readings were detected at ground level, a midland kit was applied and the car moved to an isolated track.  The shipper was contacted to dispatch a repair company.  SRS was contacted by the shipper.  It was determined that this was the fist load since being requalified at the shop.  The car was monitored until it could be transferred, then cleaned and purged.  After cleaning the PRD was sent to a facility to be tested and determined that it was set to operate at 159 psi.  Car is in hold waiting an OTMA

column169: At 1350 ET, Jeremiah Faustinos with XPO terminal UPH notified ERTS of a cargo release. It was reported that an estimated amount of 2-Gallons of UN3103 Organic Peroxide Type C released due to pressurizing during transit. The release impacted trailer #3233003. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched a contractor to perform cleanup activities.  Contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 50 gallons of product released to 15'x8.5' area of the trailer floor due to excessive heat. Contractors transferred product, empty jerricans, impacted absorbents to 3 drums, 4 totes and 10 CUYD's.  The waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.  All liquid product was salvaged and transferred into poly jerricans and sent on to customer.

This event remains under investigation.

The car passed an outbound mechanical inspection at the previous station in Columbia, SC where the car was last switched.

column169: Package was brought to QA with visible leakage and a strong odor. Upon further inspection it is revealed that the drum had a loose lid/ seal failure leading to the spill, we believed it to be non hazardous at first. We had to reach out to the shipper to get the SDS which caused the initial delay in the DPR, however when provided the transport section did not have any information about it being hazardous, but we suspected it being hazardous because of the SDS chemical composition as well as the GHS classifications listed. We processed the DPR and ISF and asked for an updated SDS from the shipper and the delay from then to filling out an incident report was because the shipper sent us an SDS with the transport information today, however the SDS itself seems to have some conflicting items as it is classified as non hazardous but a UN#, class, as well as packing group were provided right below , it also has acute toxicity NFPA label and a skull and crossbones GHS label but no other information in the transport section about them. The proper shipping name I entered is what I found on the ERG however one was not provided on the SDS. I will include both SDS's for reference.

When loading a pallet into a trailer the forklift operator did not realize the forkblades on the forklift were protruding from the pallet they were handling and when they went to stage the pallet in the trailer they struck a drum already staged in the trailer with the protruding forkblades, puncturing it and contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured drum.
column170: Forklift operators need to be aware of the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column169: On 8/31/2024 tank car TILX 135685 was called in with an odor. During the initial assessment, the tank car was found with a manway cover gasket and a nozzle gasket. The cover gasket was deteriorated and cut causing an obstruction and a vapor release. The nozzle gasket showed no signs of issues. The cover gasket was removed as it is not needed when you have a nozzle gasket in place, and because it was damaged.  GrayMar Environmental assisted with the response.
column170: Spoke with shipper about inspecting their tank cars prior to releasing the tank car.

The shipment was discovered leaking during sort operations while unloading a bulk truck. The outer box was significantly wet and damaged. attachment Name:thumbnail_IMG_9628.jpg

When picking drum up at the customer the driver failed to make sure the bungs were tight and when tipping drum over on the dolly liquids started dripping from the bung. The driver did not notice the leek until he had made it to his truck and noticed the little trail left behind. We had a crew come out to the facility and due a thorough cleaning of the material from the floor and disposing of the absorbents used in the appropriate manner.
column170: The driver was retrained on the proper closure procedures when picking up containers.

column169: XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XQC. It was reported that approximately 5 ounces of UN1263 Barn & Outbuilding Semi-Gloss Exterior Oil Bright Red was released from a 5-gallon metal pail due to improper loading by terminal XCF. The release impacted trailer #3191199. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with PPE available on-site.  The damaged pail and clean up debris were containerized into a 20-gallon poly drum, which was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On August 17, 2024, at 1400 hours, personnel in the CSXT Mulberry Yard discovered tank car TEIX 3132, loaded with Elevated Temperature Liquid, NOS (Asphalt) appeared to have product adhering to side of tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Vertex Energy, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024081700082). Hulls Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to inspect the car.  Response personnel confirmed asphalt adhering to side and top of tank car, additionally it was noted that product had released due to an improperly secured manway cover. Specifically, 4 of the 8 manway cover swing bolts not applied; 4 of the 8 manway cover swing bolts were less than tool tight; and the manway cover gasket wis aligned.  Contractor personnel inspected and reinstalled the gasket, and properly secured the manway cover for transportation.  All hazardous product adhering to the exterior of the tank was removed.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Scott Ehrlich at 281-799-8576).

column169: On August 18, 2024, TAG inspected trailer V 007244, booking SEA 1049003. This load sailed NB on the Midnight Sun Voyage 24129 that departed Tacoma on 8/14/2024. Upon inspecting it, TAG found undeclared hazardous items of 3 boxes of UN0012 Cartridges for Weapons, Inert Projectile and 4 boxes of UN0012 visible labeled limited quantity marked Cartridges for weapons both items are Class 1.4S explosives. There were other hazardous products in the trailer that were a Class 4.1 Flammable Solid which creates an incompatibility with the 1.4S explosives. The trailer was placarded as 4.1 and should have been placarded as Class 1.4S and segregated from the 4.1 product. Once discovered an updated Manifest was requested and trailer placarded correctly.
column170: TOTE requires shippers would offer for transport undeclared hazarouds items to conduct a Hazardous Corrective Action. There corrective action from our customer is listed below: The sales and OPS team have had meetings with 2 of the shippers, and we are scheduling more to cover all who have issues these last couple of months. column43: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column169: While working in MR05 track, Harrison Yard, Memphis, TN, a CN Mechanical employee observed a clear liquid leaking from the top of UTLX 125236, (Load, Sulfuric Acid, UN1830,) down the side of the tank car to the ground. CN Mechanical Supervisor notified CN Dangerous Goods Officer (DGO) Vaughan and CN Police.  CN Dangerous Goods Officer (DGO) Vaughan performed an inspection of the tank car and found the liquid line cap to be #less than tool tight# and easily manipulated by hand, was actively leaking from the threads onto the tank car and to the ground. Additionally, the air valve plug was found #less than tool tight# and could be manipulated by hand. The air valve was in the fully closed position.  The CN Dangerous Goods Officer (DGO) responded to the site and slowly vented through the air valve to depressurize the tank car. The DGO applied new Teflon tape and tightened the liquid eduction line cap tool tight using a 24# pipe wrench. New Teflon was applied to the air valve plug and properly installed and tightened #tool tight# using a 24# pipe wrench. A CN contractor responded to decontaminate the tank car and the ground. Tank car was secured and set out to the CN Car Shop to await requalification by MRU.

During a customer site pickup, an incident occurred involving a drum of Isopropanol. A Veolia employee was reorganizing the box truck when the accident happened. While using a drum cart to relocate the Isopropanol container, the drum was improperly secured and fell backwards onto the cart. As a result, one of the cart's forks punctured the drum.  The puncture caused approximately 2 gallons of Isopropanol to spill. Prompt action was taken to address the situation. The spilled material was thoroughly cleaned up and disposed of in accordance with proper procedures. To prevent further leakage, the damaged drum was placed inside an overpack container.
column170: This incident highlights the importance of proper drum handling and securement techniques during transportation and storage operations.   Following the incident, a safety briefing was conducted with all Veolia field service personnel. The briefing emphasized two key points:  1) The importance of regularly inspecting and maintaining material handling equipment to ensure it is in proper working condition; and   2) The critical need to securely fasten all packages, containers, and drums during any movement or transportation.  This reminder aimed to reinforce best practices in handling hazardous materials and prevent similar incidents in the future. Management stressed that these safety protocols are essential for protecting employees, customers, and the environment from potential hazards associated with chemical spills or leaks.

Two Veolia employees were unloading a trailer at the Veolia Henderson TSDF, when a pressurized drum was observed. The drum was contained on a pallet on the trailer floor, but appeared to be slightly leaning. An employee attempted to carefully move the drum to a position where it could be managed and depressurized. While re-positioning, the base of the drum split away from the bottom chime, and caused approximately 45 gallons of waste flammable liquids to release onto the trailer floor, secondary containment beneath the trailer, and the receiving dock. The two employees immediately went inside of the office building and contacted Veolia's Emergency Coordinator to report the spill at 22:55 MST. The Emergency Coordinator arrived onsite at 23:30 MST and verified the released material as UN1993 Waste Flammable Liquids at 00:06 MST. A D001 reportable quantity of 100 lbs triggered a report of the incident to the NRC. The NRC report began at 00:17 MST (NRC Report Number 1408646). The spill was also reported to the Colorado Department of Public Health & Environment (CDPHE) using the online environmental spill release report form, submitted at 00:36 MST. Veolia personnel conducted in house cleanup of the released material using absorbent material, and then pressure washed the area. No injuries or exposures occurred.
column170: To prevent recurrence, Veolia reviewed the requirements to complete a thorough container inspection prior to moving a container, and the expectations of the procedure to follow when employees discover a pressurized container.

On August 2, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1760 was crushed in transit and released approximately thirty (30) gallons of product to the trailer interior, surrounding cargo asphalt, and nearby catch basin. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. A drum head vacuum was used to collect and containerize approximately 100 gallons of UN1760 impacted water from the catch basin of the storm drain into two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal. It was determined that the product remained contained to the catch basin and did not migrate or threaten to impact any waters of the state. Granular absorbents, absorbent pads, and neutralizer were used to remediate the impacted surfaces. The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 85 gallons drum for disposal purposes. All UN1760 impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal purposes.

column169: The package was discovered while offloading the first inbound trailer of the day during the start of pre-load sort at around 3:15am wet/leaking.  The package was then placed into a line bin & brought to QA for processing.  Upon inspecting the packages exterior, the shipping label had a "No-Air" marking underneath the ground symbol, & and a slip that contained a Safety Data Sheet for the contents inside was found on one side of the box.  It was also discovered that the package did not have any Hazmat/Hazmat paperwork &/or Limited Quantity markings on the package which raised some concerns.  Upon opening the package 4 1-gallon cans of Seal For Life Industries Temper Kote 1000 41 Silver Industrial Heat Coating were found soiled & with the lids popped off causing them to leak contents.  3 out of 4 were also badly bent/dented & crushed on several areas of the can.  None of the 4 cans had paint clips to help prevent the lids from popping off & no packing material was inside the package to protect the cans exteriors. According to Spidr image the package appeared to be unharmed when viewing overhead images of the package at MIDD hub, meaning the package may have loaded improperly & damaged in transit as a result.  When referencing Section 14 under DOT classification in the Safety Data Sheet it was discovered the contents are classified as Packing Group 2 & as a Class 3 Flammable Liquid.  Several packages were leaked on as a result of the spill but were able to be successfully repacked.  The portion of the leftover cardboard from the repacks were held at the QA cage to be placed into the line salvage drum per cleanup.  The Improper Shipping Form & Damaged Package Report were filled out.  Contents & cardboard were placed into a line salvage drum & sealed.  Large rubber green gloves & blue nitrile examination gloves were used when handing the hazardous material & an additional line bin was used as a precautionary measure.

Truck was traveling north with cruise control set at 61 mph and failed to negotiate a turn. Truck tracked off right side of road onto soft shoulder comprised of sand and gravel. Driver over-corrected and slowed which caused. trailer to jack-knife and overturn onto roadway. Impact of trailer to roadway and abrasion from dragging along road caused two compartments of trailer to be breached. Trailer terminated across both lanes of highway. Trailer sustained damage to rear and center compartments. Rear compartment was damaged due to impact that caused a greater than 12-inch crack along the outer trailer wall and internal vertical wall between rear and center compartment. Center compartment sustained multiple pittings and an approximate 4-inch vertical crack on the side that abraded along roadway (See attached pictures). Absorbent materials consisting of pads, booms and granular matter was dispensed immediately. Emergency response and spill response crews were notified and cleanup activities began immediately by pumping out remaining contents of trailer and removing trailer from roadway along with cleanup of roadway and visible fuel. Soil excavation activities began on August 5, 2024 upon receipt of encroachment permit from Idaho Department of Transportation.
column170: A root cause analysis was performed after the incident. Additional training has been incorporated and changes in hiring practices and identifying candidates were established. In addition, guidelines on the usage of cruise control were developed and are under review for implementation.

column169: On August 8, 2024, eight (8) 5-gallon pails of printer ink were crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site.  TLE placed all damaged product into 55-gallon waste drums. The pallet carrying the freight was cut up and placed into waste drums. Granular absorbents and hand tools were utilized to remediate the site. All spent absorbents, damaged product, and the impacted pallet were collected and containerized into five (5) 55-gallon drums

column169: On Aug 8th, a package was noticed during the PM sort to be emitting a small amount of smoke and had a burning smell.    After opening the package they discovered one of the smaller packages in side had burned through, causing scorch marks on other inner containers as well as a burned hole in the inner support material. The package contained cellphones, other lithium batteries as well as misc phone related accessories.  The fire had burned itself out by then and the package was isolated to ensure no further conflagration occured.   No injuries were reported.    After the package had cooled down it was placed into a steel salvage drum and is being held pending further investigation.

Appropriate PPE was donned, and the car was mounted. Once the housing was opened and Ice removed, it was determined that the Liquid Line Valve was open, and the Liquid Line Plug was loose. column169: QA personnel was called to Trailer #830652 for a potential HAZMAT package that was leaking; inspection of package verified that there was a leak of a Class 8 HAZMAT containing four individual 1 gallon jugs of sulfuric acid from the DIYchemicals/Cheboys brand. Package was isolated into a red tote and removed to the station HAZMAT cage to begin damaged package process for HAZMATs. Further inspection of the package interior verified that one out of four bottles of sulfuric acid had a loosened safety cap, resulting in the gradual spill of its contents inside the package, which remained mostly contained inside the package. Some of the cardboard box the items came in was eaten away from the spillage. There was also little to no inner packing material inside the package securing the hazardous items; there was a little bit of bubble packaging material inside, but not enough to secure the bottles, which allowed for space inside for the items to move around inside the package during transport, which resulted in damage and spillage occurring.

First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 3ft-by-3ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that one hundred and fifty (150) gallons of material released from one (1) 330-gallon poly tote due to a forklift puncture. The remaining product was transferred to a new poly tote and deployed a neutralizer to the impacted area and then used granular absorbents. The spent material was recovered and containerized into five (5) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: at 0100 hrs. while inspecting their train, the WLE Gambrinus Yard train crew, noticed tank car TILX 305022 at Gambrinus Yard leaking vapor from the top of the car.  They notified the WLE Gambrinus Yardmaster who then contacted myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE.  When I arrived, I could her the car leaking vapor from on top the car.  The leak was substantial, but just vapor, no liquid. I climbed the car and removed seal # 0672272 from the protective housing lid.  I investigated and found no leak inside the protective housing.  Upon further investigation, it was concluded that the leak was coming from the gasket connection between the pressure plate and the tank car nozzle.  The pressure plate stud bolts appeared to be tight.  There was no way to stop the leak.  The leak was coming from the left side of the housing.   I called CHEMTREC at 0127 hrs. to make a report and have them contact Marathon Petroleum in order to give me assistance.  Jennifer Johnson, the emergency contact from Marathon called me at 0158 to inquire about the report.  The CHEMTREC Report number was 2024080100010.  I told her what was going on and that I would be calling 911 to request the Stark County HAZMAT Team.  I also told her that I would be calling Enviroserve out of North Canton, Ohio to come out and do an emergency transfer of the car since that was the only way we could stop it from leaking.  She agreed and had me make the calls.  I called 911 at 0210 hrs.  I called the Timken Steel Security folks to have them stop all traffic on their access road that parralels the location of the incident, so that they would be no chance for ignition from any of their equipment.  I called Enviroserve at 0219 hrs. and briefed them on the situation and told them we needed and emergency transfer and then a flaring and purging of the car afterwards.   I called the Stark County Spill Report Line at 0234 hrs. to report the incident.  After we got the HAZMAT Team out and started doing air monitoring, I called to make a report with the Ohio EPA at 0505 just as a courtesy to report the vapor release.  We had 7 area rays set up for air monitoring and discovered that the vapors were going straight up and not really concentrating around the car or anywhere else at ground level.  No evacuations were required since the yard itself is isolated.  We started to Transload the car at about 0800 hrs.  We started to flare the car of its residual vapors at about 1430 hrs. and finished at 2230 hrs.  The car was labeled with Do Not Load and Home Shop Stickers and was stenciled “Cleaned”.

column169: a consist of 5 Iocomotives(2 of which was a mother/slug set PAL 2119/PAL 2112) that was fueled and prepared for an evening outbound train at the Paducah Diesel shop(3700 Starnes Avenue) was transported from the shop to the north end of paducah yard(approximately 1/2 to 3/4 of a mile) to put on oubound train set to depart that evening. The crew first used the power to pull some cars from the rip track to set over into a track and then backed in to track #8 to couple into outbound train before.pulling it to the north end of yard to stage for outbound crew. Once train was parked at north end of track#8, the conductor noticed fuel Ieaking from the PAL 2119 mother Iocomotive out the overflow on fuel tank. The crew reported it to diesel shop immediately and were instructed to shut the fuel transfer breaker off on the slug unit PAL 2112 and the leak stopped. E3 environmental(Enhanced Environmental and Emergegency) was contacted and showed up to yard to clean all affected areas. Clean up was completed and all tracks put back in service at 2050. The manual transfer switch on the PAL 2119 was later determined to be the cause of the overflow. The PAL 2119 was calling for fuel transfer when it was already full. This switch was replaced to prevent event from happening again.

Patrick stated he found the 4lbs box in the nose of the trailer and stated it looked like the box was crushed by other freight in transit . Patrick stated he was not to sure if the product was still in the container in the box or if it had leaked out in the trailer. Safety advised Patrick to stay clear of the box and the trailer until a team could arrive to assist with the spill. Patrick stated the trailer was empty and the box was on e of the last of the freight on the trailer. Patrick stated he set the box down on the table outside the trailer and will send a photo to safety. Patrick stated he does not know if anything in on the trailer floor and did not feel comfortable going back in the trailer.

column169: XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release. ERTS dispatched a contractor to assist with cleanup. Lone Star Hazmat Response, LLC was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted an 8ft-by-20ft area of the trailer floor and a 1ft-by-1ft area of concrete underneath the trailer and estimated that eight (8) gallons of material was released. Lone Star Hazmat Response, LLC personnel moved all the boxes from the pallet to verify the damage, deployed absorbents, and then cleaned the released material. The damaged cardboard, containers, and recovered material was placed into six (6) 55-gallon poly drums and was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization.

column169: On August 27, 2024, one (1) 30-gallon drum of UN3266 was punctured in transit and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from E3 Environmental (E3) to remediate the impacted site. E3 personnel deployed neutralizers and granular absorbents to the trailer interior and wooden pallet and swept them in with hand tools. The crew took apart the pallet and containerized it in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged drum of product was containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. All spent absorbents and neutralizers were collected and containerized into the same (1) 55-gallon vented drum as the wooden pallet.

column169: The package was discovered while offloading the first inbound trailer of the day during the start of pre-load sort at around 3:15am wet/leaking.  The package was then placed into a line bin & brought to QA for processing.  Upon inspecting the packages exterior, the shipping label had a "No-Air" marking underneath the ground symbol, & and a slip that contained a Safety Data Sheet for the contents inside was found on one side of the box.  It was also discovered that the package did not have any Hazmat/Hazmat paperwork &/or Limited Quantity markings on the package which raised some concerns.  Upon opening the package 4 1-gallon cans of Seal For Life Industries Temper Kote 1000 41 Silver Industrial Heat Coating were found soiled & with the lids popped off causing them to leak contents.  3 out of 4 were also badly bent/dented & crushed on several areas of the can.  None of the 4 cans had paint clips to help prevent the lids from popping off & no packing material was inside the package to protect the cans exteriors. According to Spidr image the package appeared to be unharmed when viewing overhead images of the package at MIDD hub, meaning the package may have loaded improperly & damaged in transit as a result.  When referencing Section 14 under DOT classification in the Safety Data Sheet it was discovered the contents are classified as Packing Group 2 & as a Class 3 Flammable Liquid.  Several packages were leaked on as a result of the spill but were able to be successfully repacked.  The portion of the leftover cardboard from the repacks were held at the QA cage to be placed into the line salvage drum per cleanup.  The Improper Shipping Form & Damaged Package Report were filled out.  Contents & cardboard were placed into a line salvage drum & sealed.  Large rubber green gloves & blue nitrile examination gloves were used when handing the hazardous material & an additional line bin was used as a precautionary measure.

column169: FRA Hazmat Inspector John Powell identified GATX 286323 with residue on exterior of car during an inspection at the BNSF Terminal in Spokane, WA on 8/26/2024.  The source appeared to come from the man way area and all man way swing bolts were inspected and found to be tool tight.  Upon arrival to the BNSF Railway Pasco, WA Terminal the car was then identified again by BNSF Mechanical who were aware of the prior inspection and removed the man way lid to inspect the gasket.  The gasket was identified as an insert gasket on the man way lid but was also identified as deteriorated due to no longer having the compression to allow a complete seal on the nozzle.  BNSF Mechanical HM Responders removed the gasket and replaced with a man way nozzle gasket to allow continued movement.
column170: Ensure gaskets are checked for deterioration and aging for compression prior to securement and offering for transportation.(NAR:209)

Material handler immediately placed damaged drum on its side, so that the hole was facing upwards and preventing further material from being released. column63: Defective Component or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column169: Carrier picked up load from Shipper between 05:00 and 07:00 with no spilled material observed by Driver or other paries, drive to other scheduled stops which involved multiple loading events with no spills observed by Driver or other parties, load arrived back at home terminal at 11 :49 where it was not handled further until a leak was observed by another Worker at the home terminal at 13:08, spill containment trays deployed, other materials offloaded to access the leaking container which was near the front of the trailer, the container was laid down to stop the leak and to assess the source, container was overpacked, manifest updated, driveway and parking lot inspected for signs of leak which was not observed, concluded based on location of spill and volume that leak had begun shortly before observation, Shipper notified, and load sent to final destination on 09/29/2024 using the same EPA Manifest 017958543FLE.  Source of leak found to be small round hole underneath drum; shape of hole was not conducive to damage from the used handling equipment, edges of hole were not pressed inward and not conducive to indication of a puncture, inner rim of the drum's bottom side displayed signs of wear as though metal was aged despite a newer layer of paint. Determined that bottom face had been painted over a weakened surface of the container and that the contents of the drum could have contributed to breaking through paint and an already degraded structural material.
column170: Inspected inventory of new and reconditioned drums to determine if other drums displayed similar indications of inadequate quality; none found.  Inform Reconditoner of event and findings so that they can be aware of observed discrepancy with container condition and with a potential gap within their reconditioning process or with the quality of containers they source before beginning the reconditioning process.  Inform Shipper of event and findings so that they can be aware and make a determination of whether they want to continue using drums from the current Reconditioner or exchange existing and future inventor for those from another Manufacturer.

column169: On August 21, 2024, RDX contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) of a release in Apopka FL. It was reported that 1100 gallons of Azone 15 was due to a roll over accident where police and fire department were onsite, the release impacted asphalt and soil. It was reported that the impacted area was 200ft x 8ft and 1100 gallons released, 50 gallons were confined inside the trailer and the rest impacted the roadside and the soil. Hull was dispatched to perform all onsite clean-up activities. A wrecker was called to load the trailer involved in the accident, once turned upright there was product found in the bottom of the trailer which as neutralized and solidified. Hulls has (9) 250 gallons totes that were savaged and send back to the shipper. (2) roll offs containing impacted soil, oil dry and damaged totes were used for disposal.

A semi truck tipped over, hitting a reflector post while taking NB Highway 52 ramp from WB Interstate 90. The incident was reported to the authorities and an emergency response team was called to help. Bay West field staff arrived on site and checked with Olmstead County Hazmat Team and Rochester Fire. A safety briefing was held prior to any assessment or cleanup activities began.  Two field staff suited up in level B PPE to make and initial assessment of the spill. During the initial incident assessment, the semi truck was observed to have overturned onto its side on the Hwy 52 Northbound ramp. The totes and drums within the trailer were flipped from their original position and were sitting with the openings resting on the roof of the trailer. The contents of some of the containers were observed to be still leaking onto the trailer and running out into the vegetation within the right of the way. A large plume of vapor was observed exiting a hole within the roof of the trailer due to a reaction from the chemicals. (It is believed that the vapor was from the non-hazmat products). Entry into the trailer was made to collect PH sample from the products on the floor, assess damage to the containers, and take an inventory of the contents.  Due to the products still gassing, causing a plume of vapor, a confined space fan was set up to vent out the trailer while staff were working. After the initial assessment was conducted, a cleanup plan was made to pump out and transfer the container into new totes. Field Staff began setting up and prepares to transfer the remaining product from the containers. Two staff made entry into the trailer and began to make openings into the hydrogen peroxide totes so a stinger pipe could be used to reach the bottom. Once all of the hydrogen peroxide totes were transferred, 55 gallons of water were flushed through the hoses and pump to decontaminate it before moving onto the next product. After the flush, field staff continued the same process to the remaining products within the trailer until all the totes were empty.  A second crew arrived on site to relieve the initial response crew. A safety briefing  was conducted along with a discussion about the remaining work prior to the first crew mobilizing off site. The second crew began with recovering and overpacking the remaining drums within the trailer. Four drums were still intact, three of the drums were observed to be compromised and damaged, and one drum was empty. The three compromised drums were overpacked and prepared for transport. Once all of the drums were removed, absorbent pads were used to recover any remaining product from the trailer. After all of the product was removed from the trailer, a wrecking crew arrived to upright the semi and move it off site to their storage yard. All of the drums and the waste product that was transferred into totes was delivered to a MnDOT facility in Stewartville until disposal could be arranged. The total transferred product tota
column170: Cargo Securement and Driver Training is the fundament for preventing incidents while in transit. There has to be more control over the shipping procedures that the hazmat shippers have, as many times, the carriers are struggling to make them change their loading process, so that the cargo can be fully immobilized and well secured. As the carriers are subject to more inspections, while they transport the products, very often they are facing the consequences of the poor management of the loading facilities, and these facilities continue to work using the same procedures as very often they are hiding in the shadows of the carriers. Shippers and Brokers should be held as responsible as the carriers are, because this business is controlled fully by the say of the brokers and the shippers. The brokers have the authority to assign the load to another carrier, and the shippers have the ability to ask the driver to leave their facility when they do not like to be told that their procedures are not compliant. It is very hard to survive in this industry and make a living when the people that have to work in a team with you, do not share the same responsibilities as you.

column169: About 30 minutes after take off from ORD passenger Richard Grelson advised the flight crew he dropped his phone because it was getting hot in his pocket. The flight attendant then got the fire containment bag and retrieved the phone and placed it in the fire thermal runaway bag for the remainder of the flight. The CA called into TUS to advise about the overheated phone. Upon meeting the aircraft, CSM retrieved the bag from the flight attendant. The phone was no longer over heated and was then returned to the customer after deplaning the aircraft. Passenger Richard was sitting in 14e. We were in the middle of the service when he told me that his phone was hot. I asked if it was just charging and he said no it was in his pocket and the phone wasn't working. I immediately grabbed the phone and grabbed the fire containment bag. After putting the phone in the bag I took it and put it in the cart in the aft galley. I then asked passenger Richard what happened before the flight and he said he dropped the phone before boarding the flight and the phone turned off and didn't work after that. He thought it was ok. Then his phone started to get hot in his pocket. I told the captain everything. Then the csm took it once we were fully deplaned in Tucson.

column169: Discovered during the OB sort. Package is a damaged, undeclared limited quantity hazmat. Outer box has no indication that package is a hazmat, but inner package does. Caps were loose on bottles, and seals were defective. Package was also loaded on its side because there were no exterior orientation arrows to indicate there were liquids inside. The combination of these two facts lead to leakage into and out of container.
column170: Ensure that all hazmats, whether limited quantity or fully regulated, are properly marked and labelled. This includes diamond labels and orientation arrows. Ensure all caps are tight and all seals are in proper order.
